{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488903"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:01:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"570"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/570"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.05,0.04,0.76,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/570"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85786"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1554"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36578"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-week history of abdominal discomfort and fever. He reports increasing abdominal distension, now associated with shortness of breath and dizziness when lying down. He has a medical history of hypertension, atrial fibrillation, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include perindopril, aspirin, clopidogrel, and metformin. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and reports drinking about a glass of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. He has scleral icterus. His abdomen is distended but not tense, with prominent superficial veins, shifting dullness, and bilateral scrotal swelling. There is a flexion deformity of the 4th left digit. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transaminase: 90 U/L (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate transaminase: 180 U/L (5-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 30 \u00b5mol/L (2-24)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 28 g/L (34-48)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EINR: 2.5 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Congestive cardiac failure","Nephrotic syndrome","Cholelithiasis","Alcoholic liver disease","Acute pancreatitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of decompensated liver cirrhosis, which is most commonly due to excessive alcohol consumption, metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease (previously non-alcoholic fatty liver disease), or hepatitis C infection. In this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcoholic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis, despite the patient reporting only drinking one glass of wine a day. It\u0027s important to note that patients often underreport their alcohol consumption when questioned by healthcare providers. A clue to this underlying aetiology is the AST:ALT ratio being \u0026gt;2, highly suggestive of alcohol-related liver disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stigmata of liver cirrhosis seen in this patient include ascites (abdominal distension with shifting dullness), jaundice (scleral icterus), and caput medusae (prominent superficial abdominal veins). The mention of the flexion deformity of the 4th left digit likely refers to Dupuytren\u0027s contracture, which is commonly associated with alcohol-related liver disease, although also seen in those with repetitive handling, cigarette smoking, and diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests show signs of hepatocyte damage (elevated transaminases and bilirubin) and impaired hepatic synthetic function (low albumin and elevated INR).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongestive cardiac failure\u003C/strong\u003E can result in ascites in severe cases. However, the additional findings of scleral icterus, transaminase derangement, and prolonged INR suggest that the patient\u0027s presentation is due to liver failure rather than cardiac issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrotic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by profound proteinuria, peripheral oedema, hypoalbuminaemia, and hypercholesterolaemia. While some of these findings are consistent with the patient\u0027s presentation, the INR derangement and scleral icterus are more indicative of decompensated liver failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholelithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the formation of gallstones. On its own, it does not cause decompensation of liver function and the associated findings provided in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E should be considered in patients with epigastric abdominal pain. However, given the subacute onset of symptoms (approximately four weeks) and the pattern of liver enzyme derangement, it is unlikely in this instance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, the combination of clinical features (ascites, jaundice) and laboratory findings (elevated transaminases, hyperbilirubinaemia, hypoalbuminaemia, and coagulopathy) strongly suggest decompensated liver cirrhosis, with alcoholic liver disease being the most likely underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common causes of liver cirrhosis are alcohol abuse, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, and hepatitis C.","Decompensated liver cirrhosis presents with ascites, jaundice, coagulopathy, and impaired synthetic function.","Patients often underreport their alcohol consumption when questioned by healthcare providers."],"references":["Mansour D, McPherson S. Management of decompensated cirrhosis. Clin Med (Lond). 2018;18(Suppl 2):s60-s5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6334027/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85786"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"570"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85786"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T19:05:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T19:06:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"570"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103365"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description